│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1.          │
│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe opt crash is an assertion failure in            │
│ ArrayRef::slice asserting N+M <= size(), triggered inside SLP vectorizer's    │
│ tryToVectorizeGatheredLoads when processing masked gathered loads. This       │
│ indicates an out-of-bounds slice request on an ArrayRef<LoadInst*>.\n\n2.     │
│ Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe debug log shows the crash occurring after 'Trying   │
│ to vectorize gathered loads' and while handling masked gathers. The backtrace │
│ points to lambdas inside BoUpSLP::tryToVectorizeGatheredLoads, specifically   │
│ around line 6906 where the code marks masked gather candidates as vectorized. │
│ Earlier, slices of loads are created with a safe length using                 │
│ std::min(NumElts, E - Cnt). Later, when marking masked gathers, the code      │
│ slices using a fixed NumElts without min, which can exceed the remaining      │
│ element count near the array end.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nIn              │
│ GetVectorizedRanges, the loop over Cnt creates 'Slice' as                     │
│ ArrayRef(Loads).slice(Cnt, std::min(NumElts, E - Cnt)). When                  │
│ LS==ScatterVectorize, it records Cnt in MaskedGatherVectorized. After the     │
│ inner loop, it iterates MaskedGatherVectorized and constructs Slice using     │
│ ArrayRef(Loads).slice(Cnt, NumElts). This second slice uses NumElts directly, │
│ which can be larger than Loads.size()-Cnt if the recorded slice near the end  │
│ had fewer than NumElts elements. This violates the ArrayRef::slice bound      │
│ check, causing the assertion.\nAdditionally, when updating StartIdx after     │
│ marking as vectorized, it uses StartIdx += NumElts, which is also incorrect   │
│ for the final partial slice and can desynchronize index tracking.\n\n4.       │
│ Proposed Edit Point(s)\n- File:                                               │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp, lines 6905-6914.\nReplace    │
│ the construction of Slice and the StartIdx update to use the actual           │
│ vectorized slice length rather than assuming NumElts.\n\nSuggested change:\n- │
│ Before: \n  ArrayRef<LoadInst *> Slice = ArrayRef(Loads).slice(Cnt,           │
│ NumElts);\n  ArrayRef<Value *> Values(\n      reinterpret_cast<Value *const   │
│ *>(Slice.begin()), Slice.size());\n  Results.emplace_back(Values,             │
│ LoadsState::ScatterVectorize);\n  VectorizedLoads.insert(Slice.begin(),       │
│ Slice.end());\n  if (Cnt == StartIdx)\n    StartIdx += NumElts;\n\n- After:\n │
│ size_t Len = std::min<unsigned>(NumElts, Loads.size() - Cnt);\n               │
│ ArrayRef<LoadInst *> Slice = ArrayRef(Loads).slice(Cnt, Len);\n               │
│ ArrayRef<Value *> Values(\n      reinterpret_cast<Value *const                │
│ *>(Slice.begin()), Slice.size());\n  Results.emplace_back(Values,             │
│ LoadsState::ScatterVectorize);\n  VectorizedLoads.insert(Slice.begin(),       │
│ Slice.end());\n  if (Cnt == StartIdx)\n    StartIdx += Slice.size();\n\nThis  │
│ ensures the slice is always within bounds and the StartIdx is correctly       │
│ advanced by the actual number of elements vectorized.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe  │
│ crash is due to an out-of-bounds ArrayRef slice when marking masked gather    │
│ candidates as vectorized, caused by using a fixed NumElts rather than the     │
│ actual remaining length. By bounding the slice length with std::min(NumElts,  │
│ Loads.size() - Cnt) and updating StartIdx by Slice.size(), we prevent the     │
│ assertion failure and maintain correct indexing and bookkeeping for masked    │
│ gather vectorization."})                                                      │
