│                                                                               │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The opt crash is an assertion failure in ArrayRef::slice asserting N+M <=     │
│ size(), triggered inside SLP vectorizer's tryToVectorizeGatheredLoads when    │
│ processing masked gathered loads. This indicates an out-of-bounds slice       │
│ request on an ArrayRef<LoadInst*>.                                            │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The debug log shows the crash occurring after 'Trying to vectorize gathered   │
│ loads' and while handling masked gathers. The backtrace points to lambdas     │
│ inside BoUpSLP::tryToVectorizeGatheredLoads, specifically around line 6906    │
│ where the code marks masked gather candidates as vectorized. Earlier, slices  │
│ of loads are created with a safe length using std::min(NumElts, E - Cnt).     │
│ Later, when marking masked gathers, the code slices using a fixed NumElts     │
│ without min, which can exceed the remaining element count near the array end. │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ In GetVectorizedRanges, the loop over Cnt creates 'Slice' as                  │
│ ArrayRef(Loads).slice(Cnt, std::min(NumElts, E - Cnt)). When                  │
│ LS==ScatterVectorize, it records Cnt in MaskedGatherVectorized. After the     │
│ inner loop, it iterates MaskedGatherVectorized and constructs Slice using     │
│ ArrayRef(Loads).slice(Cnt, NumElts). This second slice uses NumElts directly, │
│ which can be larger than Loads.size()-Cnt if the recorded slice near the end  │
│ had fewer than NumElts elements. This violates the ArrayRef::slice bound      │
│ check, causing the assertion.                                                 │
│ Additionally, when updating StartIdx after marking as vectorized, it uses     │
│ StartIdx += NumElts, which is also incorrect for the final partial slice and  │
│ can desynchronize index tracking.                                             │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)                                                     │
│ - File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp, lines 6905-6914.     │
│ Replace the construction of Slice and the StartIdx update to use the actual   │
│ vectorized slice length rather than assuming NumElts.                         │
│                                                                               │
│ Suggested change:                                                             │
│ - Before:                                                                     │
│   ArrayRef<LoadInst *> Slice = ArrayRef(Loads).slice(Cnt, NumElts);           │
│   ArrayRef<Value *> Values(                                                   │
│       reinterpret_cast<Value *const *>(Slice.begin()), Slice.size());         │
│   Results.emplace_back(Values, LoadsState::ScatterVectorize);                 │
│   VectorizedLoads.insert(Slice.begin(), Slice.end());                         │
│   if (Cnt == StartIdx)                                                        │
│     StartIdx += NumElts;                                                      │
│                                                                               │
│ - After:                                                                      │
│   size_t Len = std::min<unsigned>(NumElts, Loads.size() - Cnt);               │
│   ArrayRef<LoadInst *> Slice = ArrayRef(Loads).slice(Cnt, Len);               │
│   ArrayRef<Value *> Values(                                                   │
│       reinterpret_cast<Value *const *>(Slice.begin()), Slice.size());         │
│   Results.emplace_back(Values, LoadsState::ScatterVectorize);                 │
│   VectorizedLoads.insert(Slice.begin(), Slice.end());                         │
│   if (Cnt == StartIdx)                                                        │
│     StartIdx += Slice.size();                                                 │
│                                                                               │
│ This ensures the slice is always within bounds and the StartIdx is correctly  │
│ advanced by the actual number of elements vectorized.                         │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The crash is due to an out-of-bounds ArrayRef slice when marking masked       │
│ gather candidates as vectorized, caused by using a fixed NumElts rather than  │
